  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 건부(乾符)를 …… 곤진(坤珍) : '
    value: 건부곤진(乾符坤珍)은 천지가 제왕(帝王)을 돕는 상서(祥瑞)를 말한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 금성(金城)의 만치(萬雉) : '
    value: 치첩(雉堞)이 만이나 되는 큰 성이란 말이다. 치첩은 지금도 동대문에 남아 있는데, 활쏘는 구멍을 뚫어 놓은 그것이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 천록(天祿)ㆍ석거(石渠) : '
    value: 천록각(天祿閣)ㆍ석거각(石渠閣)은 한(漢)나라의 비서(秘書)를 쌓아둔 집이다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 숭문(崇文) : '
    value: 숭문관(崇文館)은 위(魏)나라 명제(明帝)가 글 잘하는 문사(文士)들을 모아서 거처시킨 집이다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 금란(金鑾) : '
    value: 당나라 한림학사(翰林學士)들이 거처하던 집이다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 우리 성상(聖上)은 …… 본받아 : '
    value: 임금은 원(元)을 체(體)하고, 신하는 원(元)을 조화(調和)한다는 말이 옛 글에 있다. 원은 천지의 덕의 근본을 말한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 자유(子游)ㆍ자하(子夏) : '
    value: 공자의 제자 중에 문학을 잘한 사람이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 소보(巢父)로 …… 못하게 하고 : '
    value: 요(堯)가 허유(許由)에게 천하를 사양하였더니 허유는 더러운 소리를 들었다고 영수(穎水)에 귀를 씻었다. 소보(巢父)는 허유가 귀 씻은 물이 더럽다고 송아지를 상류(上流)에 몰고 가서 물을 먹이었다. 여기서는 잘못 인용하였다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 안합(顔闔)은 …… 뚫지 못하리 : '
    value: 안합(顔闔)은 노(魯)나라 처사(處士)인데, 임금이 억지로 불러서 사자(使者)가 문으로 들어오니 그는 뒷담을 뚫고 도망하였다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 아침저녁 …… 헌납(獻納)하네 : '
    value: 논사(論思)는 나라 다스리는 도리를 의논하고 생각함이요, 헌납(獻納)은 좋은 계책을 임금에게 바침이다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 김(金)ㆍ장(張) …… 허(許)ㆍ사(史) : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 김일제(金日磾)의 자손 장안세(張安世)의 자손이 대대로 좋은 벼슬을 하였고 허씨는 선제(宣帝)의 처가요, 사씨(史氏)는 그의 외가이다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 업후(鄴候) : '
    value: 당나라 이업후(李鄴候)집에 책이 3만 권이나 있었다.
  - key: '[주-D013] 목천(木天) : '
    value: 당나라 비서각이 가장 높고 크므로 그것을 목천(木天)이라 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D014] 영주(瀛洲) : '
    value: 당나라 태종(太宗)이 글 잘하는 18명의 학사(學士)를 모아서 우대하니, 당시의 사람들이 그들을 신선이 사는 영주(瀛洲)에 올랐다고 부러워하였다.
  - key: '[주-D015] 운대(雲臺) : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 명제(明帝)가 남궁운대(南宮雲臺)에 28장을 그렸었다.
  - key: '[주-D016] 귀신이 …… 아니런가 : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 유향(劉向)이 밤에 천록각(天祿閣)에서 책을 교정하는데, 옆에 한 노인이 청려장 끝에다 불을 켜 가지고 비춰 주면서, “나는 하늘의 태을성(太乙星)인데, 인간에 묘금(卯金) 유(劉)란 선비가 책을 교정하므로 와서 도와주노라.” 하였다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D017] 용건(龍巾)으로 …… 아니런가 : '
    value: 이백이 한림학사(翰林學士)로 있을 때에 당명황(唐明皇)이 글을 짓게 하려고 부르니 이백이 밖에서 술이 취하여 들어와서는 구토(嘔吐)를 하였다. 임금이 친히 수건으로 그것을 닦아 주었다.
  - key: '[주-D018] 금련촉(金蓮燭)을 …… 아니런가 : '
    value: 소동파(蘇東坡)가 한림학사로 있을 때에 임금에게 불려 가서 밤늦도록 있다가 나올 때에 임금이 어전(御前)에만 쓰는 금련(金蓮) 촛불을 들려서 보내 주니 사람들은 임금이 오는가 하고 깜짝 놀래었다.
  - key: '[주-D019] 낭간(琅玕) : '
    value: 주옥(珠玉)과 같은 아름다운 돌인데, 보물(寶物)이다. 여기서는 선비들 가슴에 간직한 아름다운 포부를 헤쳐서 임금에게 바친다는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D020] 문화(文化)는 …… 불 듯하고 : '
    value: 공자의 말에, “윗사람의 덕은 바람이요, 아랫사람은 풀과 같아서 반드시 바람을 따른다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D021] 산악과 …… 아룀이요 : '
    value: 한나라 사마상여(司馬相如)가 임금에게 상림부(上林賦)를 지어 바쳤는데, 그 글 속에 큰 산과 깊은 바다를 말한 구절이 있고 또 여기서는 그 글이 산과 바다처럼 넓고 큰 기상이 있다는 뜻인 듯하다.
  - key: '[주-D022] 삼재(三才) : '
    value: 천(天)ㆍ지(地)ㆍ인(人)을 삼재(三才)라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D023] 사유(四維) : '
    value: 《관자(管子)》에, “예(禮)ㆍ의(義)ㆍ염(廉)ㆍ치(耻)를 사유(四維)라 한다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D024] 그가 “문(文)이 …… 탄식함이 : '
    value: 공자가 말하기를, “문왕(文王)이 이미 없어졌으니, 문(文)이 이(자신)에 있지 않느냐.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D025] 대들보가 이미 꺾어진 : '
    value: 공자가 세상을 떠나기 며칠 전에 꿈을 꾸고는 자기의 죽음을 미리 알고 노래를 부르기를, “태산이 무너지련다 대들보가 꺾어지련다. 철인(哲人)이 돌아가려는구나.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D026] 단목(端木)도 …… 들었고 : '
    value: 단목(端木)은 자공(子貢)의 성이다. 자공이 말하기를, “부자(夫子)의 문장을 얻어 들을 수 있다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D027] 염(濂)ㆍ락(洛)은 …… 찾았으랴 : '
    value: 주염계(周廉溪)와 정자(程子 낙양(洛陽) 사람)는 공자처럼 근원을 다 알지 못하고 아래의 흐름에서부터 위로 거슬러 찾아간다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D028] 문(文)에는 …… 가르침이로세 : '
    value: 공자의 말에, “문(文)만으로도 안 되고 바탕[質]만으로도 안 되고, 문과 질이 고루 조화되어 빈빈(彬彬)한 연후에야 군자(君子)이니라.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D029] 소인 : '
    value: 여기서 말하는 소인(小人)은 지위 낮은 백성을 말한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 眧 : '
    value: 昭
english:
  title: Ode to the Hongmungwan
  author: Lee Mok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Looking back to antiquity,
    when our ancestral kings set aside arms and cultivated letters,
    grasping the symbols of Heaven and revealing the treasures of Earth—
    they made light of what Han and Tang had wrought,
    and embraced the benevolence of Tang and Wu.
    Dust cleared beyond the borders;
    beasts returned to the fields.

    Then was the capital established in Hwayang,
    auspicious vapors rising thick as clouds.
    Golden ramparts were built ten thousand battlements high,
    standing proud on left and right of the state.
    Double gates reached toward heaven;
    thousand portals opened wide and spacious.

    In those days, common folk came like children,
    rejoicing and bearing the throne aloft.
    Lu Ban's cunning hands had scarcely finished their work
    when scholar-officials emerged—
    wings to the Ji household, like Zhou Duke and Shao Duke before them.

    Then the wise voice spoke:
    "The Changes tell us: Heaven displays its images;
    the sage takes them as models.
    To craft and create is to follow this meaning.
    Heaven contains Purple Tenuity, seat of the Supreme Ruler.
    The Regulations and Wall stars draw near—
    these are the stars of letters and culture.
    When refined essence descends, kingdoms gain wise ministers.
    When radiance multiplies, harmony returns twice over.
    Thus does Heaven assist in governing through literature.

    "Therefore arose the libraries—
    Heavenly Treasury, Stone Canal,
    and the Halls of Sublime Letters and Golden Orchids,
    standing lofty at the south of the main palace,
    majestic at the western wing of the palace.
    There the Six Arts and Hundred Schools are taught.
    There the methods of the Two Emperors and Three Kings are studied.
    This was the institution of flourishing ages,
    the supreme law for ordering the realm.

    "How much more then, with our Sage Sovereign,
    embodying the Original, establishing institutions,
    broadly extending literary virtue—
    will he cause those whose mouths once spoke of warfare
    to proclaim the winds of courtesy and deference,
    and those whose hands once drew the bow
    to grasp the brush of Masters You and Xia!"

    So it was requested:
    "Let us first establish that which presides over human culture,
    taking Heaven as our model."

    The King replied: "Indeed!"

    Great scholars heard and leaped with joy,
    their eyes shining, their hearts alert.
    Following the diviner's direction,
    silent auspice shot forth its rays upon the proper axis.
    The Mother Earth concealed nothing of her treasures.

    Then was a great hall constructed,
    expanding our noble Way.

    See how it stands:
    Rounded and verdant,
    Magnificent and glorious in its display—
    Clouds gathering, then drifting in mystery,
    Clear and bright and open.
    Like birds poised for flight,
    Like mountains pausing in their stride.
    Rainbow beams soar aloft as dragons rise;
    Cloud windows shimmer as lightning circles round.
    Silken screens frame moonlit nights;
    Bead curtains catch the spring breeze.

    Warm chambers face the sun to the south;
    Cool rooms open to the breeze from the west.
    In deepest winter, autumn garments still feel warm;
    In midsummer, one can study by the lamp's gentle glow.

    Silver screens exhale mist;
    Jade courtyards bloom with spring.
    The warm words of the sovereign pour in—
    Their immense grace seeps into my very bones.
    Rare delicacies are laid upon seven precious treasures,
    Scattered like stars in a clear sky.
    Harmony pervades the gossamer fringe;
    Auspicious vapors encircle the golden cup.

    So it is that even Nest-Father dare not wash his ears,
    and Yan Xie dare not tunnel through his wall.
    Even Boyi and Yan Ziling speak thus:
    "Why should we not return?"

    Therefore those bearing noble intentions—
    Yi Yin set down his spade in Shenye;
    Lü Wang gathered his line from the Wei—
    All come together, crowding like clouds,
    Gathering morning and night to deliberate,
    Day and night to present their counsel.

    Alas! The boundless sea suits dragons and leviathans;
    Great Mountains are not for gnats to cling to.
    Grand favor cannot be received in vain;
    Special station is not for common talents.
    Whosoever lacks the vessel for it
    Will at last entangle themselves in calamity.

    Therefore through thousand selections and hundred refinements,
    Through countless ages without cease—
    Though the Kim and Chang possessed hereditary power,
    Though the Xu and Shi held imperial kinship,
    With clans linked to three consorts
    And authority reaching across all lands,
    Yet even with thousand watchings and hundred coverings,
    They could never set one foot within.
    How much less the petty and base among men?

    Such is the name "Heaven's Hall."

    Our ancestral kings bequeathed this to later ages;
    Holy sovereigns took it as their model.
    Since the very dawn of the universe,
    Ceremonies and music, culture and arts,
    The patterns of Heaven and the principles of Earth,
    The teachings of Yin-Yang, nature and destiny—
    Ten thousand chests, a thousand racks of knowledge
    Accumulate here.

    What the Secret Archives never possessed,
    What the Marquis of Ye never heard—
    After the burning of Qin,
    All is preserved intact here.

    To gaze upon clouds of manuscripts heaped high,
    Mounds of earth piled thick—
    Jade rollers with ivory markers,
    Blue bags holding yellow books.
    Fallen pages, single characters,
    Each worth a hundred pearls.
    Cinnabar oil repels the worms;
    Wood frames rise majestic and steep.
    Though the groves of Cangwu were exposed to drying sun,
    One day could never reveal their end.

    Here Guan Lu's brilliance,
    Sei Nan's skill at reading,
    Sima Qian's comprehensive survey,
    Yang Xiong's vast erudition—
    From green spring to graying hair,
    They labored without rest.
    Yet their lips crumbled, their teeth fell out,
    And not even one part in a hundred could they retain!

    Well might they look askance at Penglai's sages,
    Well might they scorn the Cloud Terrace's honor!
    Was it not Liu Xiang whom ghosts crowned with the blue lantern?
    Was it not Li Bai whose mouth dragons wiped clean?
    Was it not Su Shi whom the golden lotus escort bore?
    Was it not Sima Guang whom righteousness pleased his lord?

    Essences of countless ages
    Gather here as one.
    What scheme remains unachieved?
    What wish proves hard to gain?
    Ten thousand principles find no obstacle in their hearts;
    A thousand ages cannot escape their words.

    They lodge in the azure clouds of distant dream,
    Their sleeves filled with Heaven's fragrant breath.
    They string pepper and orchid as their pendants,
    Listening to the South Breeze melody on Shun's zither.
    They bare the gems of jade and lapis
    Inscribed with virtues none but sage emperors can manifest.

    Culture falls like wind upon the grass,
    Becoming eyes and ears in the royal court.
    Common sentiments are brought to light,
    And the nine heavens hear the petitions ring.
    Is not this favor rooted in reason?
    Does not the sovereign's lack thus find repair?

    When tempest and rain sound mournful notes,
    They compose new verses in response.
    When ice melts and springs burst forth,
    They pour out clear thoughts in streams.
    When phoenix dances and dragon rises,
    They wield the subtle brush with freedom.
    Circumstance and principle wait upon memorials;
    Mountains and seas invoke the great compositions.
    Peaks rise majestically and broad—
    Who would fear the want of sympathetic ears?

    Yet at times, when the golden palace grows still,
    The jade hall sinks deep in night,
    Bones chilled and spirit clear—
    How could dreams disturb?
    The water clock of the world has finished its run,
    But still these sages rest in Heaven's realm.

    Then came one who asked:
    "Old words teach us:
    'Letters must come from the worthy;
    The worthy must possess letters.
    Letters are the branches of worth;
    Worth is the root of letters.'
    If now you call the집賢 the Hall of Spreading Letters,
    Is there a reason for this?
    Do you not abandon the root to grasp the branches?"

    The Master, hearing this, started as if awakened.
    He inserted his scepter and laughed:
    "Do you think 'letters' here means calligraphy and ink?
    If so, then every pale-faced youth who carves insects in mere rhetoric
    Would surely qualify as such?

    "Nay! True letters are thus:
    Heaven uses sun and moon, stars and constellations as its letters;
    Earth uses mountains and rivers, grass and trees as its letters;
    Man, standing between them, participates in all three,
    Taking loyalty and good faith as the body,
    Using punishment and government as the function,
    Making the Three Bonds the root,
    And the Four Virtues the branches.

    "The Five Emperors adhered to the body and stressed the root—
    Their expression was pristine and vast.
    The Three Kings opened the function and displayed the branches—
    Their radiance shone bright and clear.

    "After the passing of King Wen,
    Letters were lost to the world.
    Heaven alone entrusted them to one man: Confucius.
    Well might he sigh: 'Are not letters here in me?'

    "Alas, when the great beam has cracked and fallen,
    This Way took refuge in the written word,
    Binding itself to fragile bamboo strips,
    A thread that scarcely held.
    Even Duan Mu caught but a single glimpse;
    Lian and Luo traced back the current,
    Yet how could they reach the primal source?

    "And yet that source lies within the human heart,
    Persisting through ten thousand ages as though but one day.

    "Our sovereign, luminous and sage,
    Drives all creatures into the realm of peace.
    He plumbs the depths of Zou and Si,
    Following the subtle traces of the Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors.
    He scatters bright radiance to illuminate the obscure,
    Casting the virtues of Tang and Yao in utmost sincerity.

    "Fearful that sage virtue might know some flaw,
    He draws near to the aged and experienced.
    He takes the rise and fall of former ages as his mirror,
    Guarding against the wasted traces of the Golden Gate.

    "Who would not exhaust all thought and strength,
    Swearing to devote themselves this very night?

    "He purposes now to have affairs in the realm of non-affair,
    Action in the realm of non-action,
    Deep, distant, without bounds,
    Matching the letters of Heaven and Earth,
    Diffusing pure transformation through the natural Way.

    "This is why it is called the Hall of Spreading Letters."

    —∼—

    Now the hymn:

    Ah, vast and grand is our sovereign!
    He harmonizes silently with what lies above,
    Our Way flourishes—
    Built in days unnumbered,
    Guarding our great treasure,
    Merit beyond measure.

    Tiger halls and dragon towers
    Stand left and right,
    Venerated by spirits.

    Mountains rise steep and sheer,
    Mystic and awesome,
    Ah, how fearful to behold!

    Measured against the Eight Directions,
    Deep transformation overflows—
    Reaching through ages unnumbered.

    Though the name comes from Tang,
    The grand Way's practice
    Begins with us.

    Letters must have substance;
    What is called "harmony and grace"
    Comes from the sage's teaching.

    The culture of a thousand ages
    Again manifests in human hearts—
    All rejoice together.

    Rejoiced in by noble men!
    Rising early, retiring late,
    They illuminate the sovereign's virtue.

    In the realm of the great,
    What the small observe—
    Heaven witnesses it all.

    The student of the Great Academy,
    In humble reverence celebrating this grand achievement,
    Presents it to ages yet to come.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Grasping Heaven''s symbols and Earth''s treasures: References to the heavenly auspices that empower virtuous rulers.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Golden ramparts ten thousand battlements high: Refers to the magnificent walls of the capital with defensive parapets.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Double gates reaching toward heaven: The grand entrance gates of the palace complex.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Masters You and Xia (Ziyou and Zixia): Disciples of Confucius known for literary excellence.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Hall of Spreading Letters (Hongmungwan): A royal institution where scholars gather to cultivate literary and moral learning.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Nest-Father and Yan Xie: Recluses who rejected official positions; the text alludes to how even such hermits might be tempted by the honor of serving in this hall.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Changes (I Ching): The classical Book of Changes, foundational to Chinese wisdom.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Three Bonds and Four Virtues: Core concepts of governance and ethics in classical philosophy.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Confucius''s lament about letters: The Master''s famous saying that culture and virtue were concentrated in him as previous dynasties declined.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The cracking beam: Confucius''s own premonition of his approaching death, metaphorically suggesting the loss of the Way when sages pass.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zou and Si / Three Sovereigns and Five Emperors: References to the ancient sage-kings whose virtue and wisdom served as models.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The substance of letters: The deeper meaning of ''letters'' goes beyond mere calligraphy to encompass the whole moral and intellectual order of civilization.'
